@c @node Binary Installation
@c @section Binary Installation

@c @cindex installing Dezyne, binary
@c This section describes how to install Dezyne on an arbitrary system from a
@c self-contained tarball providing binaries for Dezyne and for all its
@c dependencies.  This is often quicker than installing from source, which
@c is described in the next sections.  The only requirement is to have
@c GNU@tie{}tar and gzip.

@c @subsection Generic GNU/Linux Binary

@c Installing goes along these lines:

@c @enumerate
@c @item
@c @cindex binary installation
@c @cindex downloading Dezyne binary
@c @cindex GNU/Linux
@c Download the binary tarball from@*
@c @url{@value{BASE-URL}/dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz},
@c e.g.:

@c @example
@c $ wget @value{BASE-URL}/\
@c dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz
@c @end example

@c Make sure to download the associated @file{.sig} file and to verify the
@c authenticity of the tarball against it; do something like:

@c @example
@c $ wget @url{@value{BASE-URL}/\
@c dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz.sig}
@c $ gpg --verify dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz.sig
@c @end example

@c If that command fails because you do not have the required public key,
@c then run this command to import it:

@c @example
@c $ wget @value{OPENPGP-SIGNING-KEY-URL} \
@c       -qO - | gpg --import -
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c and rerun the @code{gpg --verify} command.

@c Take note that a warning like ``This key is not certified with a trusted
@c signature!'' is normal.

@c Now, you can unpack the tarball; do something like:

@c @example
@c $ tar --warning=no-timestamp -xf /path/to/\
@c dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86-64.tar.gz
@c @end example

@c Then try:
@c @example
@c $ cd dezyne-@value{VERSION}
@c $ ./dzn --help
@c @end example

@c @item
@c Make the @command{dzn} command available from other locations or to
@c other users on the machine, for instance with:

@c @example
@c $ ln -s $PWD/dzn ~/bin/dzn
@c or
@c # ln -s $PWD/dzn /usr/local/bin/dzn
@c @end example

@c @item
@c And optionally, make the @command{dzn-env}
@c prefix-command@footnote{@command{dzn-env} can be used as a prefix for
@c using programs from your operating system, such as @command{info},
@c @command{man}, or @command{emacs}; so that they may find and use the
@c documentation and extensions that are provided in the binary release.}
@c available:

@c @example
@c $ ln -s $PWD/dzn-env ~/bin/dzn-env
@c or
@c # ln -s $PWD/dzn-env /usr/local/bin/dzn-env
@c @end example

@c @c TODO: an installer script, either taking care of system-wide
@c @c installation (/usr/local, -- /opt?) or for an ordinary user: ~/bin/
@c @c or ~/.local/bin and environment settings?

@c @item
@c Test your installation

@c @example
@c $ dzn hello
@c $ dzn-env info dezyne
@c @end example

@c @end enumerate

@c @noindent
@c and get busy Dezyne'ing, @pxref{Getting Started}!  You can skip the
@c following sections about building from source.

