@node Hello World!
@section Hello World!

Consider the trivial Dezyne interface @code{ihello_world}

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/ihello-world.dzn
@end example

It defines two events, named @code{hello} and @code{world} of type
@code{void} and a trivial protocol in its @code{behavior}: whenever the
@code{hello} trigger is received (@code{on hello:}), it responds
synchronously with a @code{world} action.

This scenario can be explored using the simulator (@xref{Invoking dzn
simulate}):

@example
$ dzn simulate doc/examples/ihello-world.dzn
(header ((client) ihello_world provides) ((sut) ihello_world interface))
(state ((client)) ((sut)))
labels: hello
eligible: hello
>
@end example

As expected, @code{hello} is the only trigger that is eligible to
execute; entering @code{hello} gives

@example
> hello
<external>.hello -> ...
... -> sut.hello
... <- sut.world
<external>.world <- ...
... <- sut.return
<external>.return <- ...
