@node A Simple State Machine
@section A Simple State Machine

The @code{ihello_bool} interface introduces stateful behavior that is
somewhat more interesting

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/ihello-bool.dzn
@end example

This example introduces some new language aspects

@table @code
@item bool idle = true;
A boolean state variable, defining @code{idle=true} as the initial
state,
@item [idle]
A @emph{guard}.  Only when the expression between the brackets evaluates
to @code{true} the @code{on} is eligible to execute.  In the initial
state, the @code{hello} trigger is the only thing that can occur.
The guard and the on are @emph{declarative} statements.  After the
declarative statements follows a,
@item idle = false;
An @emph{imperative} statement.  When @code{hello} trigger occurs, the
interface transitions to state @code{!idle},
@item on cruel: @dots{} on cruel: @dots{}
A non-deterministic choice@footnote{the caller does not resolve the choice
between the two cruel triggers, this is decided by the implementation}.
In the @code{!idle} state, @code{cruel} is accepted; it can either...
@item reply (true)
reply @code{false} and remain not idle, or
@item @{idle = true; reply (idle);@}
execute a compound of two imperative statements: Set the reply value to
@code{true} and transition to the idle state,
@item inevitable
If no @code{cruel} trigger occurs, @emph{inevitably} the @code{world}
action will occur.  @code{inevitable} is a @emph{modeling} event and is
not visible on the trail.  The effect is that @code{world} action now
has become @emph{decoupled} from the caller.
@end table

The state diagram (@xref{Invoking dzn graph}) depicts this protocol
graphically:

@image{images/ihello-bool,2in,,,.png}

This model is already interesting enough to have the mCRL2 model-checker
verify if all is well (@xref{Invoking dzn verify} and @xref{Verification
Checks and Errors})

@example
$ dzn -v verify doc/examples/ihello-bool.dzn
verify: ihello_bool: check: deadlock: ok
verify: ihello_bool: check: livelock: ok
verify: ihello_bool: check: deterministic: ok
@end example

which is luckily the case.  The model-checker can also be used to
generate all possible@footnote{the algorithm produces [traces that cover
every transition and every state} traces (@xref{Invoking dzn traces})
for @code{ihello_bool}:

@example
$ dzn -v traces doc/examples/ihello-bool.dzn
@end example

produces three trace files
(@file{ihello_bool.trace.0},@file{ihello_bool.trace.1}, and
@file{ihello_bool.trace.2}) with these traces (the order may differ):

@enumerate
@item
hello,return,world
@item
hello,return,cruel,true
@item
hello,return,cruel,false
@end enumerate

The sequence for the first trace with the asynchronous @code{world}
looks like this

@example
client          ihello_bool
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .hello             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .            return:
  .<-----------------:
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .             world:
  .<-----------------:
@end example

@noindent
and for the second trace where @code{cruel} happens looks like this

@example
client          ihello_bool
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .hello             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .            return:
  .<-----------------:
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .cruel             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .              true:
  .<-----------------:
@end example

@noindent
the third trace is looks like this

@example
client          ihello_bool
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .hello             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .            return:
  .<-----------------:
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .cruel             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .             false:
  .<-----------------:
@end example

@noindent
You may have noticed that the first two traces start and end in the
initial state, while the third trace starts in the initial state and
ends in the @code{!idle} state (also see the corresponding state
