@node Blocking in system context
@section Blocking in system context

Blocking has a direct effect on a single event, but it also influences
the rest of the system behavior.  To investigate the effects of the
@code{blocking} keyword in system context, we will describe two
examples.  In the first example we concentrate our attention on the
event interleaving at the provides ports.  The second example focusses
on the interleaving of events that originate from the requires ports.

The indirect effect of the use of the @code{blocking} keyword is
referred to as @emph{collateral blocking}.  Blocking an event means
making the caller wait by withholding its return until some state has
been reached which is indicated by another event.  To achieve this, the
other processes outside the component that is applying the
@code{blocking} keyword must be able to make progress.  Furthermore the
component must be exposed to this progress to be able to resolve the
@emph{blocking} situation by returning to its caller.

Let us recapitulate @emph{blocking} with a small example component that
will be used by each of the examples in this section.

@example
@verbatiminclude semantics/block.dzn
@end example

@image{images/block,,,,.png}

Here we see component @code{block} that withholds its return on port
@code{b} until it has received event @code{r.world}.  Remember that a
significant amount of time may pass between @code{r.hello} and
@code{r.world}.  During this time the rest system that contains our
@code{block} component could make progress, without the component
becoming aware.  If we add more system context to our @code{block}
component we can see how @emph{collateral blocking} manifests itself.
We will add component @code{collateral} as a client to @code{block}.

@example
@verbatiminclude semantics/collateral.dzn
@end example

Besides being a client to component @code{block} this component is also
a client to another regular non-blocking component.  The event sequence
trace below shows the first of the two possible scenarios implemented by
the @code{collateral} component.

@image{images/collateral0,,,,.png}

In this first scenario nothing is out of the ordinary, but now take a
look at the second event sequence trace below.

@image{images/collateral1,,,,.png}

Here we can see that during the time between @code{b.block} and
@code{b.return} the @code{world} event on port @code{w} is allowed to
occur.  This is the result of the fact that although the
@code{collateral} component is blocked on its call to @code{b.block}, it
will find @code{w.world} in its queue before returning to its caller.
And as a result, forwarding @code{w.world} as @code{h.world} will occur
before returning to its caller, which differs from the previous
scenario.  Verification of component @code{collateral} will check for
both scenarios and ensure that the component behavior complies with all
of the inteface behavior or otherwise report the non-compliant scenario.
Verification relies on the @code{blocking} annotation on port @code{b}
in order to infer the @emph{collateral blocking} scenario and check for
it.

@subsection Collateral blocking and multiple provides.

We can now revisit the blocking multiple provides example.  Instead of
making the multiplexing component responsible for the synchronization,
we can also add a level of indirection by splitting up
@code{blocking_multiple_provides} into a separate component that takes
care of synchronizing the @emph{asynchronous} behavior and a separate
multiple @code{provides} component.  The latter can be expressed as
component @code{mux} below:

@example
@verbatiminclude semantics/mux.dzn
@end example

This component, notwithstanding the @code{blocking} annotations on its
ports, behaves exactly like component @code{multiple_provides}.
However, when we bring its clients into scope we get the @code{system}
model below.

@example
@verbatiminclude semantics/collateral_multiple_provides.dzn
@end example

In its event sequence trace we can see another impact of
@emph{collateral blocking}.

@image{images/collateral_multiple_provides,6in,,,.png}

Although the behavior across the @code{mux} component is non-overlapping
the behavior of the client components is interleaved.

@quotation Note
In Dezyne blocking is implemented by means of coroutines.  Therefore the
interleaving of event sequences is a form of cooperative multi-tasking.
As a result its behavior is deterministic as opposed to
non-deterministic as in multi-threaded interleaving.
@end quotation

