@node Integrating Scheme Code
@section Integrating Scheme Code

@quotation Note
The Scheme code generator is still considered experimental; use with
caution.
@end quotation

To enable the Scheme code generator, configure by doing something like

@example
./configure --enable-languages=scheme --with-courage
@end example

Dezyne comes with a code generator for GNU Guile @pxref{,,, guile, Guile
reference manual}.  Scheme is an interesting language for using with
Dezyne.  It supports a functional programming style that can be applied
in handwritten code.

@c Not only is Scheme much friendlier than C or C++ for prototyping
@c (@pxref{Scheme vs C, Why Scheme is More Hackable Than C,, guile, GNU
@c Guile Reference Manual}).

Program code written in a purely functional style is more reasonable
than imperative code and especially so for concurrent programs
(@pxref{Chapter 3,, Modularity Objects and State, sicp, Structure and
Interpretation of Computer Programs}).  The Scheme code for Dezyne
components that is generated by the code generator (@xref{Invoking dzn
code}) can still use assignments to store state in an imperative way,
but that is not a problem as this code is verified: the most tricky
aspects of the software are left to Dezyne!

@menu
* Namespace to Module::
@end menu

@node Namespace to Module
@subsection Namespace to Module

The Scheme code generator introduces the ``namespace to module'' feature
which means that a Dezyne file, when it contains a single namespace, is
assumed to describe a module, such as found in languages like GNU Guile
(@pxref{Modules, Guile modules,, guile, GNU Guile Reference Manual}),
JavaScript (Python, etc.).  Similarly, foreigns are assumed to live in
their own module, so that this module can be used/required/imported.

Things to note:

@itemize

@item
Dezyne files that define more than one namespace are not supported for
``namespace to module'',

@item
foreigns go into their own module,

@item
interfaces used by a foreign need to go into their own Dezyne file to
avoid introducing cyclic dependencies,

@item
avoid the name @code{foreign}, the class @code{<foreign>}

@item
foreigns that use the same interfaces need to form a chain of
@code{use-module} and @code{re-export} their port accessors
(@pxref{Using Guile Modules,,, guile, Guile reference manual}).

@end itemize


@c *********************************************************************
@node The Dezyne command-line tools
@chapter The Dezyne command-line tools

@menu
* Invoking dzn::                Running Dezyne commands.
* Invoking dzn code::           Generating code from a Dezyne file.
* Invoking dzn graph::          Generating graphs of Dezyne models.
* Invoking dzn hello::          A simple sanity check.
* Invoking dzn language::       Lookup and completion.
* Invoking dzn lts::            Manipulate and query an LTS.
* Invoking dzn parse::          Checking the syntax of Dezyne file.
* Invoking dzn simulate::       Simulating Dezyne models.
* Invoking dzn trace::          Transform verify, code, and simulate traces.
* Invoking dzn traces::         Generate a set of traces.
* Invoking dzn verify::         Verifying Dezyne models.

@end menu

@node Invoking dzn
@section Invoking @command{dzn}

The @command{dzn} command is a front-end to Dezyne functions, such as
verification, code generation, simulation, etc.  Those functions all
have their own sub @code{command}:

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} @code{command} @var{command-option}@dots{} @file{FILE}...
@end example

Running @code{dzn} without a sub @var{command} shows a brief help text
and the list of available @command{dzn} commands.

The @var{dzn-option}s can be used with every @command{dzn} command and
can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --debug
@itemx -d
Enable debug output.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn}, and then exit.

@item --skip-wfc
@itemx -p
Skip well-formedness checking.

The well-formedness checking of a large program can take a significant
amount of time.  As the well-formedness check does not change a correct
@code{AST} in any way, it can be safely skipped when parsing a
previously checked and unmodified program (@xref{Invoking dzn parse}).

@item --transform=@var{trans}
@itemx -c @var{trans}
Apply transformation @var{trans} after parsing.  Use @command{dzn --help
--verbose} to show all transformations.  This option can be used more
than once.  For example,

@example
dzn code -l dzn -t add-explitic-temporaries -t -o- normalize:compounds test.dzn
dzn code -l dzn -t 'inline-functions(f)' -t -o- normalize:compounds test.dzn
@end example

will inline function @code{f} and remove redundant compound-statements
created by the inlining.

@item --verbose
@itemx -v
Be more verbose, show progress.

@item --version
@itemx -V
Display the current version of @code{dzn}, and then exit.

@end table

@quotation Note
The @var{dzn-option}s are placed between @command{dzn} and the sub command,
e.g. to increase verbosity when using @command{dzn verify}, use
@example
dzn -v verify file.dzn
@end example
@end quotation

@node Invoking dzn code
@section Invoking @command{dzn code}

@cindex code generation
@cindex executable program
While the simulator (@xref{Invoking dzn simulate}) can interpret Dezyne
code directly, to create an executable program Dezyne uses a code
generator.

This code generator, the command @command{dzn code}, generates compilable
or runnable code for a Dezyne file, such as @code{C++}.  Usually---i.e.,
except for trivial cases---this generated Dezyne code is combined with
``handwritten'' code in the target language to create a Dezyne
application, @xref{Code Integration}.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} code @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --calling-context=@var{type}
@itemx -c @var{type}
Generate an extra parameter of @var{type} for every event.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn code}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --init=@var{PROCESS}
When generating @code{mCRL2} code, use init @var{PROCESS}.  For other
language backends, this options is ignored.

@item --language=@var{language}
@itemx -l @var{language}
Generate code for language @var{language}.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Generate a trivial main for @var{model}.  This ``generated main'' can
execute an event trace read from stdin, and writes a code trace to
stderr.  @xref{Getting Started}.

@item --output=@var{dir}
@itemx -o @var{dir}
Write output to directory @var{dir} (use @code{-} for standard output).

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
When generating @code{mCRL2} code, use queue size @var{size} for
verification, the default is @code{3}.  For other language backends,
this options is ignored.

@item --shell=@var{model}
@itemx -s @var{model}
Generate thread-safe system shell for model @var{model}.
@xref{Thread-safe Shell}.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn graph
@section Invoking @command{dzn graph}

The @command{dzn graph} command can be used to generate different
graphs from a Dezyne model.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} graph @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --backend=@var{type}
@itemx -b @var{type}
Generate a diagram using backend @var{type}; one of @code{dependency},
@code{lts}, @code{state}, or @code{system} and write it to standard
output.  The default is @code{system}.

The @code{state} diagram can simplified using options @code{--hide} and
@code{--remove}.

@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}
Under the hood, @code{lts} and @code{state} use the Dezyne VM.  LTSs can
be queried and manipulated using @command{dzn lts} (@ref{Invoking dzn
lts}) and the @url{https://mcrl2.org,mCRL2} tooling.

@quotation Note
Generating an LTS for a large component or system using the VM can be
very time-consuming.  For generating an LTS using the verification
engine, see (@ref{Invoking dzn verify}) and (@ref{Invoking dzn traces}).
@end quotation

@item --format=@var{format}
@itemx -f @var{format}
Print trace in format @var{format}; one of @code{aut}, @code{dot}, or
@code{json}.  For @code{--lts} the default is @code{aut}, for other
formats the default is @code{dot}.

@quotation Note
The @code{json} can be processed by
@url{https://gitlab.com/rma.wieringa/dezyne-p5,Dezyne-P5} to draw state
and system diagrams in a browser.
@end quotation

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn graph}, and then exit.

@item --hide=@var{hide}
@itemx -H @var{hide}
Generate a state diagram and hide @var{hide} from the transitions; one
of @code{labels} (hide everything), @code{actions} or @code{returns}.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Generate graph for model @var{model}.  The default is to use the most
``interesting'' model.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for exploration, the default is @code{3}.

@item --remove=@var{vars}
@itemx -R @var{vars}
Generate a state diagram and remove variables from nodes @var{remove};
one of @code{ports} or @code{extended}.

@code{ports} Hides the state of the component's or system's ports,
@code{extended} hides the interface's or component's extended state,
i.e., all but the main (first) state variable and implies @code{ports}.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn hello
@section Invoking @command{dzn hello}

The @command{dzn hello} command can be used to test your installation;
it echos ``hello'' to standard output.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} hello
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{ide hello}, and then exit.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn language
@section Invoking @command{dzn language}

The @command{dzn language} command produces Dezyne language completion
results and location information.  It can be used by an editor or IDE to
create a rich editing experience.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} language @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --complete
@itemx -c
Show completion result; this is the default action.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn language}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --offset=@var{offset}
Use offset @var{offset} to determine context.

@item --line=@var{line},@var{column}
@itemx --point=@var{line},@var{column}
@itemx -p @var{line},@var{column}
Calculate offset from line @var{line} and column @var{column}.

@item --lookup
@itemx -l
Show lookup result.

@c XXX TODO: is dzn language --verbose really dzn --debug language?
@item --verbose
@itemx -v
Display input, parse tree, offset, context and completions.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn lts
@section Invoking @command{dzn lts}

@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}
@cindex labeled transition system
The @command{dzn lts} command can be used to manipulate and query a
labeled transition system (@var{lts}) in Aldebaran (@code{aut}) format
(@xref{Invoking dzn graph}, @xref{Invoking dzn verify}, @xref{Invoking
dzn traces}).

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} lts @var{option}@dots{} [@file{FILE}]@dots{}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --cleanup
@itemx -c
Rewrite mCRL2 labels to Dezyne, optionally remove @var{prefix} as
specified with @option{--prefix}.

@item --deadlock
@itemx -d
Detect deadlock in @var{lts} (after introduction of failures) and
produce a witness.

@item --exclude-illegal
Remove edges leading to illegal (in combination with
@option{--failures}).

@item --failures
@itemx -f
Introduce a failure for each 'optional' event into the @file{lts}.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn lts}, and then exit.

@item --illegal
@itemx -i
Detect whether @file{lts} contains @code{<illegal>} labels.

@item --livelock
@itemx -l
Detect tau-loops in @file{lts} and produce a witness.

@item --deterministic-labels=@var{label}[,@var{label}@dots{}]
@itemx -n @var{label}[,@var{label}@dots{}]
Detect whether @file{lts} is deterministic by detecting multiple edges
of @var{label} from a single state, and produce a witness.

@item --prefix=@var{prefix}
Optional @var{prefix} for @option{--cleanup}

@item --tau=@var{event}[,@var{event}@dots{}]
@itemx -t @var{event}[,@var{event}@dots{}]
Hide all @var{event}s from @file{lts}.
@item --exclude-tau=@var{event}[,@var{event}@dots{}]
Exclude given @var{event}s from '@option{--tau}' list.


@item --single-line
@itemx -s
Report each error including its trace (witness) on a single line.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn parse
@section Invoking @command{dzn parse}

The @command{dzn parse} command parses a Dezyne file and reports any
errors, both syntax errors as well as ``well-formedness'' errors.  The
Dezyne parser consists of three stages:

@enumerate
@item
The PEG parser creates a raw @code{parse-tree}@footnote{The @command{dzn
language} command (@xref{Invoking dzn language}) works on this raw
@code{parse-tree}.},
@item
The @code{parse-tree} is converted into the abstract syntax tree
(@code{AST}),
@item
A number of so-called ``well-formedness'' checks are performed on the
@code{AST} that ascertain type correctness and detect semantic errors
(@xref{Well-formedness}),
@item
After parsing, some commands perform a normalization on the @code{AST}.
@end enumerate

The well-formedness checking of a large program can take a significant
amount of time.  As the well-formedness check does not change a correct
@code{AST} in any way, it can be safely skipped when parsing a
previously checked and unmodified program (@xref{Invoking dzn}).

Usually, the parser is invoked implicitly by commands like @command{dzn
verify} and @command{dzn code}.  It can be useful to do an explicit
check for errors, for example after saving a Dezyne file (@xref{The
Perfect Setup}).  Its syntax is:

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} parse @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --preprocess
@itemx -E
Resolve imports and produce a content stream.  This pre-processed
content can also be processed later by the parser and it has the
advantage of being independent of the file-system.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn parse}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --list-models
List the Dezyne models defined in the file, with their type.

@item --locations
@itemx -L
Show locations in output @var{ast}.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Only output @var{ast} for model @var{model}.

@item --parse-tree
@itemx -t
Write the raw @var{peg} parse tree, skip generating a full @var{ast},

@item --output=@var{file}
@itemx -o @var{file}
Write @var{ast} to @var{file}, use ``-'' for standard output.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn simulate
@section Invoking @command{dzn simulate}

The @command{dzn simulate} command starts a simulation run.

Under the hood, @command{dzn simulate} uses the Dezyne VM.  The
simulator can be used to explore Dezyne models (interfaces, components,
and systems), and to interpret error traces (witnesses) from the
verification engine (@xref{Getting Started}).  It shows code locations,
state, and state transitions and produces friendly error messages.  The
simulator and verification both report the same errors (@xref{Formal
Verification}).  The simulator, however, only reports errors that it
encounters while interpreting a specific event trace.  The verifier
performs an exhaustive search for errors but only produces a witness
and does not report any context information.  Its syntax is:

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} simulate @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --format=@var{format}
@itemx -f @var{format}
Print trace in format @var{format}; one of @code{diagram}, @code{event},
or @code{trace}.  The default is @code{trace}.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn simulate}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --internal
@itemx -i
Display internal events when using the @code{diagram} trace format.

@item --locations
@itemx -l
Display locations in the trace, this implies @option{--format=@code{trace}}.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Start simulating @var{model}.  The default is the most ``interesting''
model.

@item --no-compliance
@itemx -C
Do not run the compliance check.

@item --no-deadlock
@itemx -D
Do not run the deadlock check at the end of the trail (EOT).

@item --no-interface-determinism
Do not run the observable non-determinism check on interfaces.

@item --no-interface-livelock
Do not run the interface livelock check at the end of the trail (EOT).

@item --no-queue-full
@itemx -Q
Do not run the external queue-full check at the end of the trail (EOT).

@item --no-refusals
@itemx -R
Do not run the compliance check for the failures model refusals check at
the end of the trail (EOT).

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for simulation, the default is @code{3}.

@item --strict
@itemx -s
Use strict matching of trail, i.e., the trail must contain all
observable events.

@item --trail=@var{trail}
@itemx -t @var{trail}
Use trail @var{trail}.  The default is to read from @code{stdin}.

@item --verbose
@itemx -v
Display non-communication steps in the trace, this implies
@option{--format=@code{trace}}, @option{--locations}.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn trace
@section Invoking @command{dzn trace}

The @command{dzn trace} command is a pseudo-filter to convert between
different trace formats:

@c This is kind-of define by example; should we create a more formal
@c definition?  Where?

@table @code
@item event trace (trail)
An event trace or @emph{trail} is a list of event names observable by
interacting with a Dezyne model, for example, for
@file{doc/examples/hello-world.dzn}:

@example
p.hello
p.world
p.return
@end example

@item event trace (character separated)
Some tools, such as the simulator also read an event trace separated by
a comma or a space:

@example
 p.hello,p.world,p.return
"p.hello p.world p.return"
@end example

@item code trace (arrow trace)
The Dezyne executable code can produce a trace showing the sender and
the receiver of an event on the same line:

@example
<external>.p.hello -> sut.p.hello
<external>.p.world <- sut.p.world
<external>.p.return <- sut.p.return
@end example

@item simulator trace (split-arrow trace)
The simulator produces a trace showing the sender and the receiver of an
event both on their own line:

@example
<external>.p.hello -> ...
... -> sut.p.hello
... <- sut.p.world
<external>.p.world <- ...
... <- sut.p.return
<external>.p.return <- ...
@end example

which is especially useful when the lines are prefixed with location
information.

@end table

The @command{dzn trace} command reads arrow traces and converts them to
a code trace (the default) or an event trace.  A split-arrow trace can
also be converted to an ASCII sequence diagram.  Its syntax is:

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} trace @var{option}@dots{} [@file{FILE}]
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --format=@var{format}
@itemx -f @var{format}
Display trace in format @var{format}, one of @code{diagram},
@code{event}, @code{json}, or @code{sexp}.  The default is @code{code}.

@quotation Note
The @code{json} can be processed by
@url{https://gitlab.com/rma.wieringa/dezyne-p5,Dezyne-P5} to draw
a trace diagram in a browser.
@end quotation

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn trace}, and then exit.

@item --internal
Show communication between components in the system.  When using the
option @option{--format=diagram} on a system trace, the communication
between components in the system is hidden by default.

@item --locations
@itemx -L
Show locations in output.

@item --trace=@var{trace}
@itemx -t @var{trace}
Use trace @var{trace}.  The default is to read from standard input.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn traces
@section Invoking @command{dzn traces}

@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}

The @command{dzn traces} command generates an exhaustive set of event
traces or trails for a behavioral Dezyne model.  It can also be used to
generate an @var{lts} in Aldebaran format (@xref{Invoking dzn lts},
@xref{Invoking dzn graph}, @xref{Invoking dzn verify}).

Under the hood, @command{dzn traces} uses @command{dzn code} and mCRL2.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} traces @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --flush
@itemx -f
Include @code{<flush>} events in trace.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn traces}, and then exit.

@item --illegal
@itemx -i
Include traces that lead to an illegal.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --lts
@itemx -l
Instead of generating trace files, generate an @var{lts} in Aldebaran
format.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Generate traces for model @var{model}.

@item --output=@var{dir}
@itemx -o @var{dir}
Write trace files to directory @var{dir}.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for generation, the default is @code{3}.

@item --traces
@itemx -t
Generate trace files, this is the default.  Using @option{--traces} will
generate trace files even when @option{--lts} is used.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn verify
@section Invoking @command{dzn verify}

The @command{dzn verify} command exhaustively checks a Dezyne file for
verification errors in Dezyne models.  @xref{Formal Verification}.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} verify @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --all
@itemx -a
Show all errors, i.e., keep going after finding an error.  By default,
verification stops after finding a verification error.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @command{dzn verify}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Limit verification to @var{model}, and for a behavioral component
model, to its interfaces.

@quotation Note
Verification cannot be limited to @code{system} component models;
verifying a system model is a no-op@footnote{The compositional property
of the Dezyne component-based programming paradigm guarantees that the
verification of a @code{system} component model amounts to the
verification of all its @code{interface} models and behavioral
@code{component} models.}.
@c XXX TODO: reference to compositional quality/property
@end quotation

@item --out=@var{format}
@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}
Run a partial verification pipeline to produce @var{format}.

Interesting formats are @code{mcrl2}, @code{aut},
@code{aut-dpweak-bisim}, @code{aut-weak-trace}, and
@code{aut+provides-aut}.  Use @option{--out=help} for a full list.

The verification pipeline starts by generating @code{mCRL2} code, which
is converted into an @var{lps} and then into an @var{lts}
(@xref{Invoking dzn lts}).  The @var{lts} is then manipulated further.

Using the @option{--debug} on @command{dzn} (@xref{Invoking dzn}) shows
the pipelines with all their commands that are being used, ready for
use on the command line.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for verification, the default is @code{3}.

@end table

@node Dezyne Language Reference
@chapter Dezyne Language Reference

Dezyne is a component based language as well as a method for the
development of event-driven systems.  The language has formal semantics,
which is coherently expressed in: a textual representation, a graphical
representation, a mathematical representation, a source code
representation, and the observable behavior of a machine executing the
resulting program.  The concepts available in the language denote the
different properties@footnote{ Structural: events and their direction in
an interface, ports on a component, components in a system, bindings
between the ports; behavioral: guarded triggers performing actions |
assignments | if-else | functions} that can be observed and have meaning
in one or more of the representations: textual, graphical, mathematical,
program and execution.

The @code{C}-like syntax of Dezyne should give it a familiar feel to
many programmers.  Dezyne has some unique language concepts and syntax
elements that are described in this chapter.

@menu
* Lexical Analysis::            Tokens, separators and whitespace.
* Dezyne Files::                What goes into a Dezyne file?
* Types and Expressions::       Manipulating data in Dezyne.
* Interfaces::                  Defining contracts for components and systems.
* Components::                  Defining a program's behavior in Dezyne.
* Systems::                     Decomposing a system.
* Namespaces::                  Avoiding name collision.
@end menu

@node Lexical Analysis
@section Lexical Analysis

@cindex parser
@cindex parsing
@cindex PEG
Dezyne is a @code{C}-like language.  This means that identifiers must be
separated by either whitespace, delimiters or operators and is otherwise
whitespace invariant.  The Dezyne parser is defined using a partial
expression grammar or ``PEG'' (@pxref{PEG Parsing,,, guile, GNU Guile
Reference Manual}).

@menu
* Identifiers::                 Choosing names.
* Keywords::                    Restricted words.
* Operators::                   Building blocks for expressions.
* Delimiters::                  Constructing lists.
* Lexical Scoping::             Locality of names.
* Comments::                    Explanations for human readers.
@end menu

@node Identifiers
@subsection Identifiers

In Dezyne identifiers are used to name objects like interfaces,
components, events, user defined types, variables, etc.  A keyword
cannot be used as an identifier and identifiers are case-sensitive.

@example
identifier ::= [a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z0-9_]*
@end example

An identifier starts with a letter or an underscore, which can be
followed by further letters, digits, or underscores.  The following are
all valid identifiers:

@example
p, hello, Alarm, turn_on, VALUE_123, _
@end example

@quotation Note
That by convention Dezyne identifiers are also used in the target
language, however the target language may impose further restrictions on
identifiers.
@end quotation

@node Keywords
@subsection Keywords

The following list shows identifiers that are reserved words in Dezyne,
or @emph{keywords}.  These keywords may not be used as an identifier
name.

@example
behavior        blocking        bool            component
defer           else            extern          external
enum            false           if              illegal
import          inevitable      injected        inout
interface       in              namespace       on
optional        otherwise       out             provides
reply           requires        return          subint
system          true
@end example

@node Operators
@subsection Operators

Dezyne uses infix notation for expressions.  The following are operators
in Dezyne:
@example
+       -       !
<       >       <=      >=      ==      !=      <=>
@end example

@node Delimiters
@subsection Delimiters

The following are delimiters in Dezyne, for introducing lists:

@example
(       )       @{       @}       $
@end example

and for elements in lists:

@example
,       .       ;       =
@end example

@node Lexical Scoping
@subsection Lexical Scoping

A lexical @emph{scope} adds locality to a name.  Names in one lexical
scope do not interfere (collide or shadow) with another scope.
Referring to a scoped identifier

@example
  reference :: scope* identifier
  scope :: identifier "."
@end example

Dezyne defines the following scopes:

@table @code
@item enum
The field values of an enum:

@example
enum result @{TRUE, FALSE, ERROR@};
@end example

are referenced to by using the enum type name as scope:

@example
result.TRUE
@end example

@item interface
A type defined in an interface:

@example
interface ihello
@{
   enum result @{TRUE, FALSE, ERROR@};
@}
@end example

can be used in a component, e.g., to define a variable:

@example
ihello.result status = ihello.result.TRUE;
@end example

@item behavior
All definitions in a behavior are local to that behavior and cannot be
referenced from outside it@footnote{This may change when Dezyne gains
support for hierarchical behaviors, a.k.a. submachines.},

@item port
A port is an interface instance; events that are communicated over a
port use the name of the port as their scope:

@example
provides ihello p;
@dots{}
on p.hello (): p.world ();
@end example

@item instance
An @code{instance} (or component instance), is an instance of a
component.  A port defined in a component

@example
component hello
@{
  provides ihello p;
  requires ihello r;
@}

@end example

can be referenced to by using the component instance name as their scope

@example
component sys
@{
  provides ihello sp;
  requires ihello sr;
  system
  @{
    hello h;
    sp <=> h.p;
    h.r <=> sr;
  @}
@}
@end example

@item namespace
Types defined in a namespace are referenced to by using the name of the
namespace as their scope.
@c TODO add example
@end table

@node Comments
@subsection Comments

Dezyne supports single-line and multi-line comments very similar to
@code{C}.  Multi-line comments may be nested.  All characters part of a
comment are skipped by the parser.

@example
/* This is an example of multi-line comment.
 * The line below is ignored also:
 * this component implements...
 */
component hello
@{
  provides ihello p; // a single-line comment
@}
@end example

@node Dezyne Files
@section Dezyne Files

Dezyne types, interfaces, and components are organized in files.  A
file, with extension '.dzn' by convention, may contain zero or more of
type definitions, interfaces, and/or components.

The toplevel Dezyne program text is defined as follows:

@example
text ::= root
root ::= (import | data-expression
           | namespace | type | interface | component)*
@end example

An interface can refer to a global type definition.  A component can
refer to types, interfaces and other components.  An explicit
@code{import} clause is needed when the referred information is defined
in another file.

@subsection Import

@cindex file import
@cindex import
An @code{import} clause makes available all types, interfaces and
components that are defined in another file.  From an imported interface
or component the 'public' parts are available, i.e., all information but
the interface or component behavior, or the component system details.

@example
import    ::= "import" (file-name "/")* file-name ";"
file-name ::= [a-zA-Z0-9_+.-]+
@end example

@quotation Note
That by convention the basename of the Dezyne file-name is used as the
target language basename, however the target platform may impose further
restrictions on a file-name.
@end quotation

By convention, Dezyne files use the extension @code{.dzn}.  Some
examples:

@example
import file-name.dzn;
import ../global-types.dzn;
import some/directory/prefix/library.dzn;
@end example

An imported file may contain imports itself, these are also imported.
When a file occurs twice in the resulting set of imports, it is expanded
only once.  This avoids introducing duplicate definitions.  Mutually
recursive imports are allowed (@xref{Invoking dzn parse}).

@node Types and Expressions
@section Types and Expressions

In Dezyne all variables and constants are typed.  A number of type
constructs are available.

@example
type      ::= bool / enum / subint / void
data-type ::= extern
@end example

@code{type}s are used for event reply types, variables,
function parameters, function, function return types, and function call
arguments.  @code{data-types} are used for event parameters, action
arguments, and variables.

@menu
* Void::                        Definitions without type.
* Bool::                        Builtin boolean type.
* Enum::                        Enumerated user types.
* Subint::                      Integer user types.
* Extern Data Type::            Foreign data user types.
* Expressions::                 Constants and data.
@end menu

@node Void
@subsection @code{void}

@code{void} is used for defining untyped events and functions, e.g.,

an event without reply value:

@example
in void hello ();
@end example

a function without return value:

@example
void foo ()
@{
  world;
@}
@end example

@node Bool
@subsection @code{bool}

@cindex bool type
@cindex true
@cindex false
Dezyne has a builtin boolean type @code{bool} with constants
@code{false} and @code{true}.

Available boolean operators are:

@table @code
@item !b
Logical negation of a boolean expression,
@item b1 && b2
Logical and of two boolean expressions,
@item b1 || b2
Logical or of two boolean expressions,
@item b1 == b2
Equality of two boolean expressions,
@item b1 != b2
Inequality of two boolean expressions,
@end table
where @code{b}, @code{b1}, and @code{b2} are boolean expressions.

It is used to define boolean events

@example
in bool test ();
@end example

boolean variables

@example
bool idle = true;
@end example

and parameters and functions

@example
bool negate (bool input)
@{
  return !input;
@}
@end example

@node Enum
@subsection @code{enum}

@cindex enum type
An interface or component can specify a user defined enumerated
type.  Such a type has a name and a list of values.

@example
enum   ::= "enum" identifier "@{" fields "@}" ";"
fields ::= identifier ("," identifier)* ","?
@end example

An example:

@example
enum result @{FALSE,TRUE,ERROR@};
@end example

where @code{enum} is a keyword; this defines the enum type @code{result}
with three values.

In expressions the enum values are referred to with a dot notation:
@code{result.FALSE}.

Available enum operators are:

@table @code
@item e1 == e2
Equality of two enum expressions,
@item e1 != e2
Inequality of two enum expressions,
@item v.ERROR
A field-test: testing the value of an enum variable, denoted by
@code{v.ERROR}, which is shorthand for @code{v == result.ERROR}
@end table
where @code{e1} and @code{e2} denote enum expressions, and @code{v} an
enum variable of type @code{result}.

@node Subint
@subsection @code{subint}

@cindex integer type
@cindex subint type
The integer type is available in Dezyne in a restricted way@footnote{the
subint definition allows range checking and prevents accidental
unboundedness during model checking}: only a finite contiguous subrange
of integer numbers can be used.  An explicit type definition is needed
for each subset, where a @code{C}-like syntax is used.

@example
subint  ::= "subint" identifier "@{" range "@}" ";"
range   ::= integer ".." integer
integer ::= ("-")? [0-9]+
@end example

An example:

@example
subint int @{-1..2@};
@end example

where @code{subint} is a keyword.  This defines the finite type
@code{int} with possible values -1, 0, 1, and 2.  Available integer
operators are:

@table @code

@item comparison

@table @code
@item i1
@item i1 <= i2
@item i1 >= i2
@item i1 >  i2
@item i1 == i2
@item i1 != i2
@end table

@item i1 + i2,
Integer addition,
@item i1 - i2
Integer subtraction,
@end table
where @code{i1} and @code{i2} denote integers.

@quotation note
Integers of different @code{subint} types can be used in comparison,
assignment, and function calls.  The verifier will check that the
resulting integer value is within the defined @code{subint} range.
@end quotation

@node Extern Data Type
@subsection @code{extern} data

@cindex data type
@cindex extern
Apart from @code{bool}, @code{enum}, and @code{int} types introduced
above, also @code{extern} data types can be defined.  An @code{extern}
data type is defined as follows:

@cindex data-expression
@example
extern          ::= "extern" identifier data-expression ";"
data-expression ::= "$" (!"$")* "$"
@end example

The @code{data-expression} is a type expression in the target
language.

No Dezyne-supported expressions are available for data types, apart from
@code{data-expression}s.  The content of the data-expression is passed
to the target language verbatim.

For example, a @code{C++} string type could be defined as follows:

@example
extern string $std::string$;
@end example

@node Expressions
@subsection Expressions

Expressions in Dezyne are strictly typed.

@cindex bool-expression
@cindex boolean-expression
@example
expression ::= bool-expression | data-expression | enum-expression
                | integer-expression
@end example

@quotation Note
The well-formedness check (@xref{Well-formedness}) verifies that
expressions are of the correct type.
@end quotation

@subsubheading Bool Expressions

@example
bool-expression ::= bool-literal
                     | action
                     | call
                     | field-test
                     | "!" bool-expression
                     | "(" bool-expression ")"
                     | bool-expression bool-operator bool-expression
                     | int-expression comparison-operator int-expression
bool-literal    ::= "false" | "true"
field-test      ::= enum-variable "." enum-field
bool-operator   ::= "==" | "!=" | "&&" | "||"
comparison-operator
                ::= "==" | "!=" | "<" | "<=" | ">" | ">="
@end example

where @code{action} and @code{call} are of type @code{bool}.

@subsubheading Enum Expressions

@cindex enum-expression
@example
enum-expression ::= enum-literal
                     | action
                     | call
enum-literal    ::= enum "." field
@end example

where @code{action} and @code{call} are of the correct @code{enum} type.

@subsubheading Int Expressions

@cindex int-expression
@cindex integer-expression
@example
int-expression ::= int-literal
                     | action
                     | call
                     | int-expression int-operator int-expression
int-literal    ::= "-"? [0-9]+
int-operator   ::= "+" | "-"
@end example

where @code{action} and @code{call} are of a @code{subint} type.

@node Interfaces
@section Interfaces

@cindex event
@cindex interface
@cindex message
Interfaces describe the interaction between two components: the events
(or messages) that can and cannot be communicated, i.e., the interaction
protocol.

@example
interface ::= "interface" identifier "@{" types-and-events behavior "@}"
type-and-events
          ::= (type | event)*
behavior  ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
@end example

Each event has a direction specified by the @code{in} or @code{out}
keywords.  An event labeled with @code{in} (@code{in}-event) is received
by the implementation providing the interface.  Conversely, an event
labeled with @code{out} (@code{out}-event) is emitted by the
implementation providing the interface.  Note that from the point of
view of an implementation requiring an interface the interpretation of
@code{in} and @code{out} is inverted.

The interface protocol is specified in the @code{behavior} section.

@example
$include <string>;$
interface ihello
@{
  @b{enum} result @{FALSE,TRUE,ERROR@};
  @b{extern} string $std::string$;
  @b{in} result hello (string greeting);
  @b{out} void world ();
  @b{behavior} @{ @dots{} @}
@}
@end example

@menu
* Events::                      Event or message definitions.
* Behavior::                    Specifying an interface protocol.
* Declarative Statements::      Define when to run which trigger.
* Imperative Statements::       The code that runs upon a trigger.
* Functions::                   Avoiding code duplication.
@end menu

@node Events
@subsection Events

Events are messages or function calls and returns that are communicated
between components.

@example
event     ::= direction type identifier "(" parameter-list? ")" ";"
direction ::= "in" | "out"
parameter-list
          ::= parameter ( "," parameter)*
parameter ::= parameter-direction? data-type identifier
parameter-direction
          ::= "in" | "out" | "inout"
@end example

Some examples.

A void in-event called @code{e} with an empty parameter list:

@example
in void e ();
@end example

a valued in-event called @code{e2}:

@example
in enum_type e2 ();
@end example

a void in-event called @code{e3} with two data parameters

@example
out void e3 (some_id in_id, out some_id out_id);
@end example

a void out-event called @code{e4} with a data parameter

@example
out void e4 (some_string s);
@end example

@quotation Note
There are two restrictions on @code{out}-event definitions:
@itemize
@item
@code{out}-events must be of type @code{void}, and
@item
@code{out}-events can only take @code{in} parameters.
@end itemize
@end quotation

@subsubsection Modeling Events

Apart from user-defined events, Dezyne has two special builtin events
called @code{optional} and @code{inevitable}.  These are called
``modeling events'' and are used in interface to specify
@emph{decoupled} behavior (@xref{Using inevitable and optional}).

@node Behavior
@subsection Behavior

The @code{behavior} section of an interface defines the protocol of the
interface.  The protocol prescribes the causal relation between events
and state.  The behavior is akin to a state machine.

@example
behavior ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
behavior-statement
         ::= type | variable | function | declarative-statement
@end example

@menu
* Behavior Variable::           The detailed state of the behavior.
@end menu

@node Behavior Variable
@subsubsection Behavior @code{variable}

The @code{behavior} variables define the state of the behavior.
They are sometime referred to as @emph{state variables}.

@example
variable ::= (type identifier = expression
                | data-type identifier = data-expression
                | data-type identifier) ";"
@end example

where @code{type} and @code{expression} must match.

For example:

@example
bool idle = true;
@end example

@quotation Note
The @code{expression} used in the definition of a behavior variable must
be a constant expression, i.e.: no @code{action}, @code{call} or
@code{variable}-reference is allowed.
@end quotation

@node Declarative Statements
@subsection Declarative Statements

A trigger is prescribed by an interface to be handled by an
implementation as is the condition under which it occurs.  Collectively
this is referred to as a declarative statement.  The condition is
expressed as a @code{guard}, the trigger in an @code{on}.  The code that
is executed when both the guard expression evaluates to @code{true} and
the trigger occurs, is called the @emph{imperative statement}
(@xref{Imperative Statements}).

@example
declarative-statement ::= guard | on | "@{" declarative-statement "@}"
@end example

The combination of all declarative statements leading up to a
@code{imperative statement} is also called the declarative
@emph{prefix}.  The combination of all @code{guard}s, the @code{on} and
the @code{imperative statement} is sometimes referred to as a
@emph{transition}.

@example
transition   ::= prefix imperative-statement
prefix       ::= <guards> <on>
@end example

@menu
* On::                          Defining what happens upon a trigger.
* Guard::                       Declarative trigger condition.
* Using inevitable and optional::  Nitty gritty details on using modeling events.
@end menu

@node On
@subsubsection @code{on}

The @code{on} defines which trigger is to be handled:

@example
on        ::= "on" trigger ("," trigger)* ":" statement
trigger   ::= event-name | "inevitable" | "optional"
statement ::= declarative-statement | imperative-statement | illegal
imperative-statement
          ::= action | assign | call | if | reply | return | variable
                | imperative-compound
                | empty-statement
illegal   ::= "illegal"
imperative-compound
          ::= "@{" (imperative-statement ";")+ "@}"
empty-statement
          ::= ";" | "@{" "@}"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: @{@}
on inevitable: @{world; idle = true;@}
@end example

When two or more observably distinct imperative statements are specified
for a certain trigger, the interface is said to behave
@emph{non-deterministic} with respect to the trigger.  For example:

@example
on hello: world;
on hello: cruel;
@end example

when the trigger @code{hello} is sent, the response can either be
@code{world} or @code{cruel} but which one it will be cannot be
predicted.  Non-determinism in interfaces is allowed as long as it is
@emph{observable non-determinism}, i.e., after the trigger has returned
the client should be able to know which state the interface is in.  For
example, this is not allowed:

@example
on hello: @{@}
on hello: idle = true;
@end example

and will lead to a verification error (@xref{Verification Checks and
Errors}).

@quotation Note

@itemize
@item
There must be exactly one imperative statement for every combination of
@code{guard} and @code{on},
@item
There can be only one @code{on} leading to an imperative statement.
@end itemize
@end quotation

@node Guard
@subsubsection @code{guard}

@example
guard ::= "[" bool-expression "]" statement
@end example

For example:

@example
[idle]  on hello: idle = false;
[!idle]
@{
  on hello: idle = true;
  on inevitable: @{world; idle = true;@}
@}
@end example

@node Using inevitable and optional
@subsubsection Using @code{inevitable} and @code{optional}

In interfaces, two @emph{modeling} events may be used as abstract
triggers, i.e.@: @code{inevitable} and @code{optional}:

@example
on inevitable: imperative-statement;
on optional:   imperative-statement;
@end example

Where @code{inevitable} implies that if no other triggers occur, this
trigger is guaranteed to occur, and @code{optional} implies that the
trigger may or may never occur.

Note that an inevitable event is not allways guaranteed to occur, it is
only inevitable in the absence of other events.

An example of an interface using both inevitable and optional.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/inevitable-optional.dzn
@end example

In the interface above a reply value of @code{true} on @code{hello}
informs the client sending the @code{hello} that the @code{world} can be
waited on.  However in case the reply value of @code{hello} is
@code{false} and the client would sit there waiting for @code{cruel} to
happen, they may sit there forever because @code{cruel} might never
happen.  This is what we refer to as a @emph{deadlock}.  To avoid this
@emph{deadlock} as a client, they must make sure that they can handle a
@code{cruel} in case it does happen and that they have another way of
making progress in case @code{cruel} never happens.

Conversely, the implementation of this interface may choose to perform
the cruel always, never or intermittently after a @code{hello} followed
by a @code{false}, but it must (being contractually required) always do
a @code{world} after a @code{hello} followed by a @code{true}.

@node Imperative Statements
@subsection Imperative Statements

The imperative statement is the statement that will be executed when a
guarded trigger occurs (see also @xref{Declarative Statements}).

@menu
* Action::                      Emitting events.
* Assign::                      Updating state.
* Function Call::               A named collection of imperative statements.
* Empty Statement::             When a trigger has no effect, or there is nothing to do.
* If::                          Imperative decisions.
* Illegal::                     Specifying what is not allowed.
* Reply::                       Determining the reply for a valued trigger.
* Return::                      Returning from a function.
* Variable::                    Defining a local variable.
@end menu

@node Action
@subsubsection @code{action}

When handling a trigger (a @code{in}-event), an interface can emit zero
or more @code{out}-events.  The event that follows a trigger is are
referred to as an @code{action}.

@example
action ::= event-name ";"
@end example

where @code{event-name} is the name of an @code{out}-event defined in
the interface.

For example

@example
world;
@end example

@node Assign
@subsubsection @code{assign}

The value of a previously defined variable can be updated using an
@code{assign}:

@example
assign ::= variable "=" expression ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
idle = true;
idle = !b;
idle = negate (idle);
@end example

where @code{b} and @code{idle} are variables of type @code{bool},
@code{negate} is a function with one @code{bool} parameter and
return-type @code{bool} (see @xref{Function Call}).

@node Function Call
@subsubsection @code{call}

@example
call          ::= identifier "(" argument-list ")"
argument-list ::= (expression ",")*
@end example

For example:

@example
foo ();
bar (true, 12);
@end example

Note that the value returned by a @code{call} to a non-@code{void}
@code{function} is not allowed to be ignored.  Therefore in the example
above both @code{foo} and @code{bar} must be @code{function}s of type
@code{void}.  By capturing the value in a variable definition or the use
of an @code{assign} to an existing variable is the proper way to handle
the return value:

@example
bool b = bool_function ();
b = bool_function ();
@end example

Another way is to properly use a return value is in simple expressions,
possibly combined with: @b{==}, @b{!=}, @b{!}, @b{&&}, @b{||} (since
2.14.0)

@example
if (bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function () && b) @dots{};
if (enum_function () == result.FALSE) @dots{};
if (enum_function () != result.TRUE || b) @dots{};
reply (enum_function ());
reply (enum_function () != result.ERROR);
@end example

or in any expression (since 2.16.0).

@node Empty Statement
@subsubsection Empty Statement

@cindex empty statement
@cindex skip
The empty statement or @code{skip} statement defines for @emph{nothing}
to happen.

@example
empty-statement ::=  ";" | "@{" "@}"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: @{@}
on cruel: ;
@end example

@node If
@subsubsection @code{if}

Conditional handling of statements is supported by the @code{if}, which
can have an optional else:

@example
if ::= ("if" "(" bool-expression ")" imperative-statement)
         | ("if" "(" bool-expression ")" imperative-statement
              "else" imperative-statement)
@end example

For example

@example
if (idle)
  @{world; idle = false;@}
else
  cruel;
@end example

Since 2.14.0, a valued @code{call} may be used in an
@code{if}-expression.

For example:

@example
if (bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function () && b) @dots{};
if (enum_function () == result.TRUE) @dots{};
if (enum_function () != result.ERROR || b) @dots{};
@end example

Since 2.16.0, arbitrarily complex expressions may be used.

Note that nested @code{if}s are allowed:

@example
if (b1) if (b2) then-statement else else-statement
@end example

is interpreted as

@example
if (b1)
@{ if (b2) then-statement else else-statement @}
@end example

In other words: @code{else} binds to the closest @code{if}.

@quotation Note
In an interface, an @code{illegal} is not allowed as a then-statement or
an else-statement, however the same can be expressed using a
@code{guard}.
@end quotation

@node Illegal
@subsubsection @code{illegal}

A trigger can be explicitly marked as being @code{illegal} in a certain
state.  In that case, @code{illegal} must be the only imperative
statement for that trigger.

@example
illegal ::= "illegal" ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: illegal;
@end example

@quotation Note
Since 2.14.0, a declarative-statement followed by an @code{illegal} can
be completely omitted, since it has the same meaning.  It is however
still available for backwards compatibility.
@end quotation

@node Reply
@subsubsection @code{reply}

Define the value to be returned at the end of an @code{on} with a valued
trigger.

@example
reply ::= "reply" "(" expression ")" ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: reply (true);
@end example

@quotation Note
Reply does not mean ``return'', it merely defines the value that is
returned when the @code{on} has finished executing.  @code{reply} does
not have to be the final imperative statement, however it must occur
exactly once on every path through every sequence statements.
@end quotation

@node Return
@subsubsection @code{return}

@code{return} is used to return program execution from the body of a
function to the caller, possibly providing a value.

Implicitly returning from a @code{void} function is allowed.  Also it is
not required to use @code{return} as the last statement of a @code{void}
function, i.e., an early return skipping over remaining statements is
allowed.

@example
return ::= "return" ";"
             | "return" expression ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
void foo ()
@{
  if (idle) return;
  world;
@}

bool negate (bool b)
@{
  return !b;
@}
@end example

@node Variable
@subsubsection @code{variable}

Defining a local variable is syntactically identical to a behavior
variable:

@example
variable ::= (type identifier = expression
               | data-type identifier = data-expression
               | data-type identifier) ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
bool b = true;
bool not_idle = !idle;
bool c = negate (idle);
@end example

@node Functions
@subsection Functions

A function can is used to name and reuse a sequence of imperative
statements.

@example
function ::= type identifier "(" parameter-list ")"
               "@{" imperative-statement* "@}"
@end example

For example:

@example
void foo ()
@{
  bye;
  cruel;
  world;
@}

bool bar (bool b, int i)
@{
  if (b)
    world;
  idle = i == 12;
  return idle;
@}
@end example

Functions are allowed to be called recursively.  This includes mutual
recursive functions (function @code{f} calling function @code{g} and
vice versa).  However only as long as every function involved in the
recursion is @emph{tail recursive}; which means that a recursive call is
the last statement in the function.

@node Components
@section Components

Components are the building blocks in a Dezyne.  They allow composition
into bigger components called system components.

A component has a list of ports and optionally a behavior or a system
block.

@example
component ::= "component" "@{" port+ (behavior | system)? "@}"
behavior  ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
system    ::= "system" "@{" system-statement* "@}"
@end example

@menu
* Ports::                       Defining a component's communication channels.
* Component Behavior::          Defining a component's behavior.
* Async Ports::                 Implementing decoupled behavior on top of sequential behavior.
* Component Types::             Three types of components.
* Component Declarative Statements::  Component-specific declarative statements.
* Component Imperative Statements::  Component-specific imperative statements.
* Multiple Provides Ports::     Providing more than one interface.
@end menu

@node Ports
@subsection Ports

@cindex port
@cindex provides
@cindex requires
A port is an instance of an interface.  A component has ports through
which it interacts with other components.  As such a port is one of the
two end-points connecting two components.

@example
port      ::= ("provides" interface-type identifier ";")
              | ("requires" qualifier? interface-type identifier ";")
qualifier ::= "blocking" | "external" | "injected";
@end example

The keyword @code{provides} indicates that a component implements all
of the interface behavior.

The keyword @code{requires} indicates that a component relies on some
or all of the interface behavior in its implementation.

For example:

@example
@b{provides} ihello p;
@b{provides} blocking ihello p;      // (1)
@b{requires} ihello r;
@b{requires} blocking ihello r;      // (2)
@b{requires} @b{external} itimer t;  // (3)
@b{requires} @b{injected} ilogger l; // (4)
@end example

1) provides port which may potentially block.  The @code{blocking}
qualifier must be used on a provides port when @code{blocking} is used
in the component's behavior, or when the @code{blocking} qualifier is
used on a @code{requires} port.

2) requires port which may potentially block.  The @code{blocking}
qualifier must be used on a requires port when the port it is bound to
has a @code{blocking} qualifier.

3) port to a component with a potential delay in its communication
(@pxref{External})

4) port to a shared resource (@pxref{Systems})

Furthermore a component receives its @code{trigger}s from its
surroundings through its ports.  Note that a component @code{trigger} is
either a @code{provides-in} or a @code{requires-out} event.  If the
component emits events over its ports they are referred to as
@code{action}s.  An @code{action} is either a @code{provides-out} or a
@code{requires-in} event.

@menu
* Injection::                   Ports sharing a resource.
* External::                    Ports with external delay.
@end menu

@node Injection
@subsubsection Injection

@cindex injection
A @code{requires} port can be specified to be @code{injected}:

@example
@b{requires} @b{injected} ilogger l;
@end example

This indicates that the port can be bound to a corresponding port
residing at any level in the system hierarchy.  An @code{injected} port
is the exception to the one to one rule, i.e., it allows many ports to
be connected to a single instance.  For this reason @code{out} events
are not allowed in interfaces which are @code{injected}.

@xref{Systems} for a detailed description of the binding of injected
ports.

@node External
@subsubsection @code{external}

@cindex external
The @code{external} keyword specifies that communication over a port may
experience a delay.  This may for instance be caused by the switch
between execution contexts as in inter-process communication or the use
of threads.

@example
@b{requires} @b{external} itimer t;
@end example

During verification the delay on an @code{external} interface is
experienced an additional interleaving of events that would otherwise
not occur.

@subsubsection Race condition due to external delay

Component @code{remote_timer_proxy} illustrates how a delayed
communication channel may cause a race condition leading to illegal
behavior.

The implementation of component @code{remote_timer_proxy} is correct (no
illegal behavior) for @code{requires itimer rp} but incorrect for
@code{requires external itimer rp} due to race between @code{pp.cancel}
and @code{rp.timeout}.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/remote-timer-proxy.dzn
@end example

@node Component Behavior
@subsection Component Behavior

The @code{behavior} section of a component defines its behavior.

@example
behavior           ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
behavior-statement ::= type | variable | function | async-port
                         | declarative-statement
@end example

A component behavior describes the communication or the exchange of
events between a itself and other components in its environment
connected to its ports.  Each port is defined by a local name and a
behavior refers to these ports by name when it relates @code{trigger}s
and @code{action}s (see also @xref{Ports}).

@node Async Ports
@subsection Async Ports (deprecated)

An async port is a @code{requires} of builtin type @code{dzn.async}
which is defined in the behavior of a component.

@example
async-port
  ::= "requires" "dzn.async" async-parameter-list? identifier ";"
async-parameter-list
  ::= "(" async-parameter ("," async-parameter)* ")"
async-parameter
  ::= data-type identifier
@end example

For example:

@example
requires dzn.async (int i) async;
@end example

The behavior of the builtin @code{dzn.async} port can be represented like this:

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/dzn.async.dzn
@end example

@quotation Note
The use of @code{dzn.async} is deprecated, please use @code{defer}.
@end quotation

@node Component Types
@subsection Component Types

There are tree types of component:

@table @code
@item component, regular component, or leaf
A component that defines its implementation in its @code{behavior},
@item foreign
A component that defines only ports.  Its behavior is said to be defined
elsewhere.  This is a placeholder for a component that is implemented by
some other means, like another programming language (e.g. @code{C++}),
@item system
A component that comprises other components in its @code{system}
specification, @xref{Systems}.
@end table

@subsubsection A Leaf Component

Every component in Dezyne is a leaf component, unless it is a system
component.  The following component implements one interface and a
straightforward behavior section:

@example
@b{component} hello
@{
  @b{provides} ihello p;
  @b{requires} ihello r;
  @b{requires} itimer t;
  @b{behavior}
  @{
    @b{on} p.hello (): t.create ();
    @b{on} t.timeout (): r.hello ();
    @b{on} r.world (): p.world ();
  @}
@}
@end example

@subsubsection A Foreign Component

This component does not reveal its implementation in Dezyne under this
name.  It represents a component implemented elsewhere.  It may be
implemented in another programming language, or it is implemented in
Dezyne without exposing any of its implementation details.

@example
@b{component} timer
@{
  @b{provides} itimer t;
@}
@end example

@subsubsection A System Component

A component @code{timer_system} decomposed into two components
@code{ihello} and @code{timer} where these components are connected via
their ports.

@example
@b{component} timer_system
@{
  @b{provides} ihello p;
  @b{requires} ihello r;
  @b{system}
  @{
    hello h;
    timer t;
    p @b{<=>} h.p;
    h.t @b{<=>} t.t;
    h.r @b{<=>} r;
  @}
@}
@end example

@node Component Declarative Statements
@subsection Component Declarative Statements

For a component behavior, the list of declarative statements is extended
with @code{blocking} (@xref{Blocking}).  So we get:

@example
component-declarative-statement ::= declarative-statement | blocking
@end example

Thus, in a component, the ``declarative prefix'' includes blocking such
that the prefix consists of three elements.

@example
transition  ::= prefix imperative-statement
prefix      ::= <blocking?> <guards> <on>
@end example

@menu
* Component On::                Defining what happens on a trigger.
* Blocking::                    Implementing a synchronous call on decoupled events.
* Formal Binding::              Parameter assignment in blocking or synchronous out context.
* Joining Activities::          A full blocking example.
@end menu

@node Component On
@subsubsection Component @code{on}

Similar to an interface, in a component the @code{on} defines which
trigger is to be handled.  Component triggers, however, belong to
a port and carry formal parameters:

@example
on            ::= ("on" triggers ":" statement)
                  | ("on" illegal-triggers ":" illegal)
triggers      ::= trigger ("," trigger)*
trigger       ::= port-name "." event-name "(" formal-list? ")"
formal-list   ::= formal ("," formal)*
formal        ::= identifier | (identifier formal-binding)
statement     ::= declarative-statement | imperative-statement | illegal
imperative-statement
              ::= action | assign | call | if | reply | return | variable
                  | imperative-compound
                  | defer-statement
                  | empty-statement
illegal       ::= "illegal"
imperative-compound
              ::= "@{" (imperative-statement ";")* "@}"
defer-statement
              ::= "defer" argument-list? imperative-statement
argument-list ::= "(" ")" | "(" expression ("," expression)* ")"
empty-statement
              ::=
illegal-triggers
              ::= illegal-trigger ("," illegal-trigger)*
illegal-trigger
              ::= port-name "." event-name
@end example

The @code{formal-list} to be used is defined by the parameters of the
event definition in the interface.  Their relation is position-based.
Formal parameters may introduce another name than specified in the
@code{event} definition in the interface.

For example:

@example
on p.hello (greeting): w.hello (greeting);
on p.cruel, r.hello: illegal; // Note this is optional since 2.14.0.
@end example

When two or more imperative statements are specified for a certain
trigger, the component is said to be @emph{non-deterministic}.  For
example:

@example
on p.hello (): w.hello ();
on p.hello (): ;
@end example

non-determinism in components is not allowed and will lead to a
verification error (@xref{Verification Checks and Errors}).

The @code{formal-binding} is a feature for @code{blocking} and
synchronous out event contexts @xref{Formal Binding}.

@node Blocking
@subsubsection @code{blocking}

@cindex blocking
The @code{blocking} keyword is a declarative statement that can be used
in a component.

@example
blocking ::= "blocking" statement
@end example

Using @code{blocking} requires an explicit @code{reply}.  It can only be
used in a component.  If the @code{reply} is omitted for the
@code{blocking} @code{trigger}, the imperative statement of another
@code{trigger} must perform the @code{reply} for the blocked port.
Thus, time and value of a blocked port reply depend on another
@code{trigger}.  @code{blocking} may be used once in the declarative
prefix.

Only @code{provides} ports are affected by @code{blocking}.  A call of a
provides port in-event will not return before a @code{reply} is
performed for that port.

Guards or @code{on} is commutative with respect to blocking.  If
@code{blocking} appears before a guard or @code{on} it applies
to the imperative statement after the guard or @code{on}.

@quotation Note

@itemize
@item
When @code{blocking} is used in component which is not the top component
in a system and the system has multiple @code{provide}s ports, the
system must be verified for deadlocks.  Merely verifying all individual
components is not enough.

@item
Systems containing @code{blocking} component instances must be
contained in a thread-safe shell (@pxref{Thread-safe Shell}).
@end itemize

@end quotation

For example:

@example
on trigger (): blocking imperative-statement;         (1)
@end example

@example
blocking on trigger (): imperative-statement;         (2)
@end example

@example
on trigger (): blocking [guard] imperative-statement; (3)
@end example

@example
on trigger ():
@{
  blocking [guard] imperative-statement1;             (4)
  [guard] imperative-statement2;
@}
@end example

Explanation:

2) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to the
@code{imperative-statement} following @code{on trigger:}.  This form is
semantically equivalent to 1).

3) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to the @code{imperative-statement}
following @code{[guard]}.  This form is semantically equivalent to
@code{on trigger (): [guard] blocking imperative-statement;}"

4) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to @code{imperative-statement1}.
It does @emph{not} apply to @code{imperative-statement2}.

@node Formal Binding
@subsubsection Formal Binding

A formal binding @emph{binds} a member variable to an @code{out} or
@code{inout} formal parameter.  At the moment of the @code{reply}, the
value of the bound member variable is assigned to the formal parameter.
A formal binding can be used in blocking context or synchronous out
event context.

@example
trigger        ::= port-name "." event-name "(" formal-list? ")"
formal-list    ::= formal ("," formal)*
formal         ::= identifier | (identifier formal-binding)
formal-binding ::= "<-" identifier
@end example

The @code{identifier} in @code{formal-binding} must be a member variable
of the component.

For example:

@example
extern int $int$;
component blocking_binding
@{
  provides ihello h;
  requires iworld w;

  behavior
  @{
    int g = $123$;
    bool busy = false;
    [!busy] on h.hello (n <- g): blocking @{w.hello (); busy = true;@}
    [busy] on w.world (): @{g = $456$; h.reply (); busy = false;@}
    [busy] on w.cruel (): @{h.reply (); g = $456$; busy = false;@}
  @}
@}
@end example

in the case of @code{w.world} the assignment of @code{g = $456$} before
the release of the blocked thread by @code{h.reply ()} ensures that
parameter @code{n} returns with value @code{456}.  However in the case
of @code{w.cruel} the caller of @code{h.hello} receives @code{123} via
parameter @code{n}.

For a synchronous interface @code{iworld} with behavior:
@example
on hello: world;
on hello: cruel;
@end example

a formal binding can be used in synchronous out event context:

@example
extern int $int$;
component synchronous_out_event_binding
@{
  provides ihello h;
  requires iworld w;

  behavior
  @{
    int g = $123$;

    on h.hello (n <- g): w.hello ();
    on w.world (): @{g = $456$; h.reply (true);@}
    on w.cruel (): @{h.reply (true); g = $456$; ;@}
  @}
@}
@end example

in the case of @code{w.world} the assignment of @code{g = $456$} before
the reply by @code{h.reply ()} ensures that parameter @code{n} returns
with value @code{456}.  However in the case of @code{w.cruel} the caller
of @code{h.hello} receives @code{123} via parameter @code{n}.

For a void event without reply:

@example
extern int $int$;
component synchronous_out_event_binding
@{
  provides ihello h;
  requires iworld w;

  behavior
  @{
    int g = $123$;

    on h.hello (n <- g): w.hello ();
    on w.world (): g = $456$;
  @}
@}
@end example

the caller receives the caller of @code{h.hello} receives the last
assigned value: @code{456}.

@quotation Note
The intent is to simplify this specific behavior in the future when data
flow verification is added.
@end quotation

@node Joining Activities
@subsubsection Joining Activities

Component @code{join} illustrates the use of @code{blocking} in
synchronizing a @code{starter} with the activities of two
@code{runner}s.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/join.dzn
@end example

@node Component Imperative Statements
@subsection Component Imperative Statements

@menu
* Component Action::            Sending messages over ports.
* Component If::                Imperative decisions in a component.
* Component Illegal::           Using illegal in a component.
* Component Reply::             Using reply in a component.
* Component Defer::             Decoupling execution from the client.
@end menu

@node Component Action
@subsubsection Component @code{action}

When handling the response of a @code{trigger}, a component can send one
or more events over its ports.  The sending of a
@code{provides-out}-event or a @code{requires-in} event is referred to
as an @code{action}.

@example
action        ::= port-name "." event-name argument-list
argument-list ::= "(" ")" | "(" expression ("," expression)* ")"
@end example

where @code{port-name} is the name of a port defined in the component,
and @code{event-name} is the name of an event defined in the interface
associated with the port.

Note that the @code{event} in an @code{action} statement must be of type
@code{void}.  For a valued @code{action} the @code{reply} value may not
be ignored.  A variable definition or an @code{assign} are the
appropriate ways to handle a @code{reply} value:

@example
bool b = r.bool_event ();
b = r.bool_event2 ();
@end example

or it can be used directly in a simple expression, optionally in
combination with @b{==}, @b{!=}, @b{!}, @b{&&}, or @b{||} (since 2.14.0)

@example
if (r.bool_event ()) @dots{};
if (!r.bool_event ()) @dots{};
if (!r.bool_event () && b) @dots{};
if (r.enum_event () == result.FALSE) @dots{};
if (r.enum_event () != result.TRUE || b) @dots{};
reply (r.enum_event ());
reply (r.enum_event () != result.ERROR);
@end example

or in any expression (since 2.16.0).

@quotation Note
The restriction of using only one @code{action} or @code{call} in an
expression has been lifted (since 2.16.0).
@end quotation

@node Component If
@subsubsection Component @code{if}

In a component an @code{illegal} can be used as an imperative
statement in the branch of an @code{if} as any other imperative
statement (@xref{Component Illegal}).

@example
if ::= ("if" "(" bool-expression ")" then-statement)
         | ("if" "(" bool-expression ")" then-statement
            "else" else-statement)
then-statement := imperative-statement | illegal
else-statement := imperative-statement | illegal
@end example

For example:

@example
if (error) illegal;
@end example

Since 2.14.0, one valued @code{action} or valued @code{call} may be used
in an @code{if}-expression.

Since 2.16.0, arbitrarily complex expressions may be used.

For example:

@example
if (r.bool_event ()) @dots{};
if (!r.bool_event ()) @dots{};
if (!r.bool_event () && b) @dots{};
if (r.enum_event () == result.FALSE) @dots{};
if (r.enum_event () != result.TRUE || b) @dots{};
if (bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function () && b) @dots{};
if (enum_function () == result.TRUE) @dots{};
if (enum_function () != result.ERROR || b) @dots{};
@end example

@node Component Illegal
@subsubsection Component @code{illegal}

A @code{trigger} can be explicitly marked as @code{illegal}.  In that
case, @code{illegal} must be the only imperative statement for that
trigger.

@example
on      ::= "on" illegal-triggers ":" illegal
illegal-triggers
        ::= illegal-trigger ("," illegal-trigger)*
illegal-trigger
        ::= port-name "." event-name
illegal ::= "illegal" ";"
@end example

Note that in this case the @code{trigger}'s formal parameter list may be
omitted.

For example:

@example
on p.hello,r,world: illegal;
@end example

@quotation Note
A trigger with an @code{illegal} response can also be omitted since an
@code{illegal} response is the default behavior for every
@code{trigger}.
@end quotation

In a component an @code{illegal} can be used as an imperative statement
in the branch of an @code{if} as any other imperative statement
(@xref{Component If}).

@node Component Reply
@subsubsection Component @code{reply}

A valued trigger event requires an appropriate return value in its
response handling, the @code{reply} only determines the value not the
moment of returning it:

@example
  reply (valued_expression);
@end example

@code{reply} is also used to release a blocked call (@xref{Blocking}),
or set the reply value from a synchrous context like so:

@example
  port.reply ();
  port.reply (expression);
@end example

@node Component Defer
@subsubsection Component @code{defer}

@cindex defer
@code{defer} is a keyword that may be placed in front of an imperative
statement.

@example
defer-statement
              ::= "defer" argument-list? imperative-statement
argument-list ::= "(" ")" | "(" expression ("," expression)* ")"
@end example

@code{defer} indicates that the execution of the corresponding statement
must be postponed at least until after returning back to the
caller. Note that in order for the deferred statement to execute, the
surrounding system must have reached an overall state where it can
accept new activating events, i.e., this state is a system wide run to
completion state.

The primary goal of @code{defer} is to decouple the execution of an
imperative statement from the caller.  This allows implementing an
asynchronous interface almost as concisely as implementing it
synchronously, as demonstrated by the example below.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/defer.dzn
@end example

Here we can observe the difference between synchronous and asynchronous
behavior once more.  When the @code{synchronous} boolean equals
@code{true} the @code{world} action occurs in the context, e.g. between
the @code{hello} and its @code{return}.  When @code{synchronous} equals
@code{false} the @code{world} action occurs after the @code{return}.
This behavior is clearly depicted by the following state diagram.

@image{images/defer,2.5in,,,.png}

Perhaps the @code{idle} state might seem superfluous in the example
above, however it is not.  Besides resulting in component behavior which
is not compliant with its interface, removing the @code{idle} state and
the corresponding guard would allow a client to do multiple consecutive
@code{h.hello}'s, which results in an overflow of the defer queue.

Besides state playing a role in avoiding @code{defer} queue overflow,
there is another aspect related to state and the use of @code{defer}.
In order for the deferred statement to execute, the component must
remain in the same state as it was at the time of invoking @code{defer}.
Anything that changes the state of the component after invoking
@code{defer} but before the deferred statement executes will remove it
from the queue, and thereby implicitly cancel it.  This is demonstrated
by the example below.  Note that a data member variable is not part of
the component state, and changing its value does not cancel the deferred
statement.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/defer-cancel.dzn
@end example

Here we see that the @code{cruel} event makes the component @code{idle}
again and in compliance with the interface this implies that the
@code{world} event can no longer occur.  The corresponding component
state diagram is depicted below.

@image{images/defer-cancel,2in,,,.png}

The ability to cancel a deferred statement is not always desirable. The
way to influence the skip behavior is to add an argument list of state
variables to the @code{defer} keyword.  This limits the scope of the
state which is observed by @code{defer} in deciding when to skip the
execution.  The two extreme cases are:

@itemize
@item
The full list of variables, which is equivalent to @code{defer} without
an arument list.
@item
The empty list of variables, which removes ability to cancel entirely.
@end itemize

We can see an example of a @code{defer} argument list below.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/defer-selection.dzn
@end example

Here the execution of the deferred statement must remain unaffected by
the change to the @code{cruel} state variable. We can achieve this by
only observing the @code{state} variable as the example shows or not
observing any state at all.  The latter case is left as an exercise to
the reader.

@node Multiple Provides Ports
@subsection Multiple Provides Ports

A component is not limited to a single provides port, it is allowed to
offer multiple interfaces simultaneously.  When a component provides
multiple ports it can receive @code{in}-events via any of its provides
ports.  As a result the interface behaviors of the provides ports are
effectively interleaved and the component is expected to handle that
appropriately.

When providing multiple ports, two restrictions hold for the component
behavior:

@table @code
@item V-fork
Within the handling of an @code{in}-event of a provides port, it is not
allowed to directly post an @code{out}-event on another provides port.

@item Y-fork
Within the handling of an @code{out}-event of a requires port, it is not
allowed to post an @code{out}-event to more than one provides port.
@end table

The rationale behind both limitations is that if V-forking or Y-forking
would be allowed that it potentially leads to behavior which is beyond
the scope of single component verification.

Violating of any of these restrictions is reported as a compliance
error.

Here are examples of the two types of forking that lead to a compliance
error:

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/compliance-multiple-provides-fork.dzn
@end example

@node Systems
@section Systems

A @code{system} component, or @code{system} is a component which is
composed from one or more sub components.  The @code{system} block
instantiates each of the sub components and either connects their ports
together or exposes them as its own, such that all ports are bound.

@example
system-component ::= "component" "@{" port* system "@}"
system           ::= "system" "@{" system-statement* "@}"
system-statement ::= (instance | binding)
instance         ::= component-name identifier ";"
binding          ::= end-point "<=>" end-point ";"
end-point        ::= port-name
                     | wildcard
                     | (instance-name "." port-name)
                     | (instance-name "." wildcard)
wildcard         ::= "*"
@end example

@quotation Note
A binding can have only one @code{wildcard}, @xref{Using Injection}.
@end quotation

For example:

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/top-middle-bottom.dzn
@end example

The system description shows the instantiation of the two component
instances @code{ci1} and @code{ic2} and two connections or bindings
between ports.

@menu
* Component Instances::         The components of a system.
* Binding::                     The plumbing of a system.
@end menu

@node Component Instances
@subsection Component Instances

In a system description a sub component is specified by its type and
local name:

@example
instance ::= component-name identifier ";"
@end example

The component definition of @code{component-name} has to be available,
potentially through an @code{import}.

It is allowed to have more than one instance of the same type:

@example
hello h1;
hello h2;
@end example

@node Binding
@subsection Binding

Communication between components is achieved through component ports.
The lines of communication are established by binding ports:

@example
binding   ::= end-point "<=>" end-point ";"
end-point ::= port-name
              | wildcard
              | (instance-name "." port-name)
              | (instance-name "." wildcard)
wildcard  ::= "*"
@end example

Note that bindings are symmetrical, i.e., left and right
@code{end-points} can be exchanged.  Communication is restricted to
ports of the same (interface) type.  Moreover the communication
'direction' has to be compatible.  There are two cases:

@itemize

@item
Two sub components communicating: always a @code{provides} port binds to
a @code{requires} port, like in @code{top.rr <=> middle.pp} in the
@code{top_middle_bottom} system example above.

@item
In the case of port forwarding, where a sub-component port is exposed as a
system port, the directions of the ports must be the same, like in
@code{p <=> top.pp} and @code{bottom.rr <=> r} in the
@code{top_middle_bottom} system example above.

@end itemize

@menu
* Using Injection::             Binding injected ports.
@end menu

@node Using Injection
@subsubsection Using Injection

@cindex injection
Binding of @code{injected} ports is done at a higher system level
(@pxref{Components}).  A wild-card character (@code{*}) is used to
achieve the binding of the @code{provides} port of a single instance to
all @code{injected requires} ports.

Let's take a logging interface as an example:

@example
interface ilog
@{
  ...
@}
component logger
@{
  provides ilog log;
  ...
@}
@end example

Suppose a lot of components require logging:

@example
...
component some_component12
@{
  provides some_interface12 p;
  requires injected ilog l;
  ...
@}
component some_component13 @{
  provides some_interface13 p;
  requires injected ilog l;
  ...
@}
...
@end example

then some system component can bind all logging in one go:

@example
component some_system
@{
  ...
  system
  @{
    logger clog;
    ...
    some_component12 c12;
    some_component13 c13;
    ...
    clog.log <=> *;
  @}
@}
@end example

It is allowed to group some components in a sub system:

@example
component some_sub_system
@{
  ...
  system @{
    ...
    some_component12 c12;
    some_component13 c13;
    ...
  @}
@}
@end example

and use the wild-card binding for that sub system:

@example
component some_system
@{
  ...
  system
  @{
    logger clog;
    some_sub_system subsys;
    ...
    clog.log <=> subsys.*;
  @}
@}
@end example

@node Namespaces
@section Namespaces

@cindex scoping
@cindex namespace
All component, interface, and type definitions are defined in a
@code{namespace}, which provides name scoping.  The scope is used as a
prefix when referring to the name from another scope.

@example
namespace      ::= "namespace" identifier "@{" namespace-root "@}"
namespace-root ::= (namespace | type | interface | component)*
@end example

For example:

@example
namespace space
@{
  extern string $std::string$;
  interface ihello
  @{
     enum result @{FALSE, TRUE, ERROR@};
     in result hello (string s);
     out void world ();
     behavior
     @{
       on hello (s): reply (result.TRUE);
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

@subsection Namespace Extension

It is allowed to spread the definition of types, interfaces, components,
and sub-namespaces over multiple instances of a namespace scope.  This is
most useful since in a 'real' project definitions are spread over
multiple files.

So

@example
namespace space
@{
  extern string $std::string$;
  interface ihello @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example

is equivalent to

@example
namespace space
@{
  extern string $std::string$;
@}
namespace space
@{
  interface ihello @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example

@subsection Referencing

When within namespace @code{space} the type @code{string} is defined,
then outside that namespace it is referred to by prefixing it with the
name of that namespace and a dot, as in: @code{space.string}.

Within its own namespace the short name @code{string} is also accepted.

In complex cases it may be necessary to refer to the default
@emph{global} namespace which has an empty name; this results in a
namespace prefix starting with a dot, as can be seen in the following
(somewhat convoluted) example.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/inner-space.dzn
@end example

which defines:

@itemize

@item interface @code{foo.I} with local enum @code{foo.I.Bool}
@item interface @code{inner.foo.I} with local enum @code{inner.foo.I.Bool}
@item component @code{inner.space}
@item component @code{bar.c}
@end itemize

The two variables defined in component @code{inner.space} have types
@code{foo.I.Bool} and @code{.foo.I.Bool} respectively.  The first type
expands to @code{inner.foo.I.Bool} since it is defined in namespace
@code{inner}.  The starting dot in the second definition prevents this
expansion.

@node Well-formedness
@chapter Well-formedness

The syntax as defined in @ref{Dezyne Language Reference} leaves room for
certain combinations and variations that would lead to Dezyne code that
cannot be translated to an mCRL2 process algebra specification.  This
chapter describes a collection of well-formedness checks that are
defined on top of the syntax.

Apart from the syntax checks performed by the parser, five additional
categories of checks can be identified:

@table @emph
@item definition checks
Upon failure, these produce a @code{undefined identifier} error,
@item parameter checks
Upon failure, these produce a @code{count mismatch} error,
@item type checks
Upon failure, these produce a @code{type-mismatch} error,
@item shadowing checks
Upon failure, these produce a @code{shadowing} error,
@item well-formedness checks
Semantic checks, a.k.a. ``well-formedness'' checks.  Upon failure, these
produce a @code{well-formedness} error.
@end table

The first four categories are common programming errors and should not
need additional explanation.  The last category---the well-formedness
checks---are unique to Dezyne and are described in this chapter.

@menu
* Well-formedness Checks Categories::  Types of checks.
* List of Well-formedness Checks::  An alphabetical lookup list.
* Well-formedness -- Top level::  Interfaces, events and components.
* Well-formedness -- Directional::  Direction of trigger and action.
* Well-formedness -- Nesting::  The right place for declarative and imperative.
* Well-formedness -- Mixing::   Mixing of declarative and imperative.
* Well-formedness -- Reply::    Reply and ports.
* Well-formedness -- Valued Actions and Calls::  Careful use of values.
* Well-formedness -- Injection::  Restrictions on injection.
* Well-formedness -- Functions::  Returning and recursing.
* Well-formedness -- Data Parameters::  Data type errors.
* Well-formedness -- System::   Correctly binding all ports.
@end menu

@node Well-formedness Checks Categories
@section Well-formedness Checks Categories

Well-formedness checks on the @code{behavior} part of a model come in a
number of categories:

@table @emph

@item Top level
Interface, event and component definitions.

@item Directional
@code{trigger}s and @code{action}s are expected at different places
depending on the direction of their @code{event}.

@item Nesting
The imperative part of the language (@code{assign}s, @code{action}s,
function @code{call}s) are only allowed in an imperative statement or in
a function body,

@item Mixing
The use of statements within @code{compound}s is restricted,

@item Reply
The usage of @code{reply},

@item Valued Actions and Calls
The use of non-@code{void} @code{action}s and @code{call}s,

@item Injection
The use of @code{injected} ports,

@item Functions
A function body should be imperative, and have a well-defined return.

@item Data Parameters
The use of data parameters,

@item Injection
The use of @code{injected} ports,

@item System
All ports should be bound correctly.

@end table

@quotation Note
A trigger is an event that occurs and is prefixed by @code{on} in the
behavior, an action is an event that is emitted inside the imperative
body of a trigger.
@end quotation

